ions whose parameters are unknown. It can be used for density estimation, clustering and anomaly detection.  \n","\n","Gaussian mixture model takes the number of Gaussian distributions $k$ as a predefined hyperparameter. The dataset $X$ (without target) is assumed to have been generated through the following probabilistic process:\n","\n","- For each instance, a cluster is picked randomly among $k$ clusters. The probability of choosing the $j$th cluster is defined by the cluster's weight $\\phi(j)$.\n","\n","- This chosen cluster for the $i$th instance is noted $z(i)=j$.\n","- The location x(i) of this instance is then sampled randomly from the Gaussian distribution with mean $\\mu(j)$ and covariance matrix $\\Sigma(j)$.\n","\n","The estimation of $\\mu(j)$ and $\\Sigma(j)$ relies on the **Expectation-Maximization (EM) algorithm**. Similar to KMeans, EM also initializes the cluster parameters randomly, then it repeats two steps\n","until convergence, first assigning instances to clusters (this is called the expectation step) then updating the clusters (this is called the maximization step)\n","\n","Assume one variable $x$ is a mixture of two normal distributions (labeled by 0 and 1). We first randomly choose values for the unknown parameters $\\theta = (\\phi_0, \\phi_1 , \\mu_1, \\mu_2, \\sigma_1, \\sigma_2)$\n","\n","**E-step**\n","\n","Give the parameters, the conditional distribution of Z is determined by Bayes theorem.\n","\n","$$P(Z_i=j|x_i,\\theta) = \\frac{\\phi_if(x_j|\\mu_j,\\sigma_j,z_i=j)}{\\sum \\phi_k f(x_i|\\mu_k,\\sigma_k,z_i=k)}$$\n","\n","**M-step**\n","\n","Set $Z_i = arg\\max_j P(Z_i=j|x_i,\\theta)$ and estimate $\\phi,\\mu,\\sigma$ for each group.\n","\n","repeat\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"d_rEC2_q2csh"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["from sklearn.datasets import make_blobs\n","X, y = make_blobs(n_samples=100, centers=3, n_features=2, random_state=1)\n","\n","for i in range(3):\n","  plt.scatter(X[y==i,0],X[y==i,1])\n","\n","plt.show()"],"